{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2045"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2045"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.52,0.04,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103623"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2045"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86040"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35910"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103623"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-month-old boy presents to a small rural Emergency Department. His parents report he had seizure-like activity that morning. He has also had reduced feeding, diarrhoea and vomiting for the past two days. On examination, he appears flat and lethargic with a temperature of 39.0\u00b0C. He is resting in his mother\u0027s arms with his eyes closed and becomes irritable when the room light is turned on. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lumbar puncture","Commence antibiotics and antivirals","Transfer to regional centre for CT imaging","Discharge with regular paracetamol for febrile seizures","Admit for observation and supportive measures"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy\u0027s presentation of fever with possible photophobia raises a strong suspicion for meningo-encephalitis. The most important immediate management is to promptly administer empiric \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics and antivirals\u003C/strong\u003E. This should be continued until CSF microscopy can confirm the causative organism. Treatment should not be delayed for \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003ECT imaging\u003C/strong\u003E, as delayed treatment is associated with poorer outcomes and death - however a lumbar puncture can be considered at an appropriate and safe time. Administering anti-infectives does not significantly interfere with the ability to identify the causative organism, as highly sensitive PCR testing is used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELocal guidelines should be consulted for the most appropriate anti-infective regimen. Typical antibiotics include cefotaxime 50 mg/kg IV 6-hourly up to 2 g or ceftriaxone 50 mg/kg IV 6-hourly, with or after dexamethasone 0.15 mg/kg (2.0-10.0) 6-hourly, as there is limited evidence it may reduce hearing loss. An antiviral such as aciclovir 10-20 mg/kg should also be given to cover HSV encephalitis. If the child is shocked, a 20 mL/kg normal saline bolus can be given. For infants less than 2 months old, benzylpenicillin should be added to cover Group B Streptococcus and Listeria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimply \u003Cstrong\u003Edischarging with paracetamol\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmitting for observation\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate, as the child requires immediate treatment. A \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is important for diagnosis but should not delay starting antibiotics. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer for CT imaging\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if the child deteriorates, but is not the immediate priority.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Local guidelines should be consulted for the most appropriate anti-infective regimen for meningitis in children.","Empirical antibiotics and antivirals should be commenced immediately in suspected meningitis without waiting for lumbar puncture or imaging.","Delayed treatment of meningitis is associated with poorer outcomes including death and neurological sequelae."],"references":["Encephalitis [published 2025 March]. In: eTG complete [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2025 May","Mine JR, Heegaard W, Mapes A, Biros M. Presentation, time to antibiotics, and mortality of patients with bacterial meningitis at an urban county medical center. J Emerg Med 2001;21(4):387-92. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11728765/","van de Beek D, Cabellos C, Dzupova O, Esposito S, Klein M, Kloek A., et al. ESCMID guideline: diagnosis and treatment of acute bacterial meningitis. Clinical Microbiology and Infection. 2016 May 1;22(Suppl. 3):S37\u2013S62. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27062097/","Brouwer MC, McIntyre P, Prasad K, van de Beek D. Corticosteroids for acute bacterial meningitis. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2015;(9):CD004405. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26362566/","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital. [Internet]. Accessed from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Meningitis_Guideline/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86040"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2045"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86040"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T21:02:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T21:03:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2045"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103623"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduat